## The People of the Book (153-162)

Before getting to Jesus, the surah addresses the People of the Book (Jews and Christians) with a series of reminders.

The Israelites are reminded of their history: they asked Moses to show them God directly, they worshipped the golden calf, they broke the Sabbath, they broke their covenants. Each time, God gave them chances. Each time, many turned away.

Then a correction of a specific claim:

> *"And for their saying: 'We killed the Messiah, Jesus, the son of Mary, the messenger of God...'"* (157)

Some in the Jewish community of Medina claimed (whether boasting or mocking) that they had killed Jesus. The Quran's response is one of the sharpest disagreements between Islam and Christianity.

---

## The Crucifixion (157-158)

> *"They did not kill him, nor did they crucify him, but it was made to appear so to them."* (157)

> *"Rather, God raised him to Himself. And God is Almighty, All-Wise."* (158)

Islam's position: **Jesus was not crucified**. It *appeared* that way to the people present, but God saved him and raised him up.

How exactly this happened is debated among Muslim scholars. The most common classical interpretation: a likeness of Jesus was cast onto someone else, and that person was crucified in his place. Other scholars take a more general reading: the event was simply made ambiguous to those who witnessed it.

What's **not** debated: Jesus did not die on the cross. This is a firm Islamic belief.

This puts Islam in a unique position. Christianity is built on the crucifixion and resurrection. Judaism doesn't accept Jesus as the Messiah. Islam accepts Jesus as the Messiah, accepts his miracles, accepts his virgin birth, but rejects the crucifixion. It keeps most of the Christian narrative and changes the ending.

