## Excess in Religion (171)

The surah speaks directly to Christians:

> *"O People of the Book, do not commit excess in your religion, and do not say about God except the truth. The Messiah, Jesus, the son of Mary, was only a messenger of God, and His word which He directed to Mary, and a soul from Him. So believe in God and His messengers, and do not say 'Three.' Desist, it is better for you. God is only one God. Exalted is He above having a son."* (171)

**"Do not say Three"** is a reference to the **Trinity** (Father, Son, Holy Spirit). Islam rejects this. God is one, not three-in-one. Jesus is a messenger, not a part of God.

The verse calls Jesus *"a word from God"* and *"a soul from Him."* This doesn't mean Jesus *is* God. It means he was created by God's command ("Be"), and the soul that animated him came from God, just as every soul does.

---

## Closing (176)

The surah ends with one final inheritance ruling, for cases where someone dies with no children or parents. The shares go to siblings.

An-Nisa began with orphans and ends with inheritance. The whole surah is, at its core, about **protecting the vulnerable**: orphans, widows, women, the oppressed. The laws exist because without them, the strong take from the weak.
